<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="340" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,1306,1621]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1486,1512]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Remarks.</emphasis>
Hochhuth (1871) recorded 
<taxonomicName authority="Kiesenwetter, 1850" authorityName="Kiesenwetter" authorityYear="1850" box="[629,1047,1486,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tachyusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulcata">
<emphasis box="[629,822,1486,1512]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Tachyusa sulcata</emphasis>
Kiesenwetter, 1850
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1116,1206,1486,1512]" name="Ukraine" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
(“…Flüsschen Lebbedj”). Gusarov studied these specimens in 1991, and identified them as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Erichson, 1839)" authorityName="V. Gusarov" baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[955,1280,1522,1549]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Brachyusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="concolor">
<emphasis box="[955,972,1523,1548]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[985,1085,1522,1548]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">concolor</emphasis>
(Erichson, 1839)
</taxonomicName>
, a widespread species in the western Palaearctic Region (
<bibRefCitation author="Schulke, M. &amp; Smetana, A." box="[637,934,1558,1585]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" refId="ref20057" refString="Schulke, M. &amp; Smetana, A. (2015) Staphylinidae. In: Lobl, I. &amp; Lobl, D. (Eds.), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. Vol. 2. Hydrophiloidea - Staphylinoidea. Revised and Updated Edition. Brill, Leiden, pp. 304 - 1134." type="book" year="2015">Schülke &amp; Smetana 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The designation of the lectototype was the result of a confusion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
